Readings: Basics of HTML, CSS & JS
Below you will find some reading material, code samples, and some additional resources that support the topic for this class and the upcoming lecture.


1. Why is it important to use semantic elements in our HTML? One of the most important features of HTML5 is its semantics. Semantic HTML refers to syntax that makes the HTML more comprehensible by better defining the different sections and layout of web pages.


2. How many levels of headings are there in HTML?
One

3. What are some uses for the <sup> and <sub> elements? The <sup> tag defines superscript text and the sub element represents a subscript.


4. When using the <abbr> element, what attribute must be added to provide the full expansion of the term?
The <abbr> tag defines an abbreviation or an acronym, like "HTML", "CSS", "Mr.", "Dr.", "ASAP", "ATM". 


Learn CSS
5. How CSS Is Structured?
The basic structure of CSS includes basic syntax of selecting the HTML element using CSS Selectors and styling the selected element using CSS properties.

6. What are ways we can apply CSS to our HTML?
There are three ways to add CSS to HTML. You can add inline CSS in a style attribute to style a single HTML element on the page. You can embed an internal stylesheet by adding CSS to the head section of your HTML doc. Or you can link to an external stylesheet that will contain all your CSS separate from your HTML.

7. Why should we avoid using inline styles?
hey go against every one of the best practices: Inline styles don't separate content from design: Inline styles are exactly the same as embedded font and other clunky design tags that modern developers rail against.Mar 8, 2020

